This operation converts the date input value from one date/time format (specified by dateFormat) to another date/time format (specified by outFormat) using locale settings (language and country).
You can use the flow "Get Current Date and Time" to check upon the default date/time format from the Java environement.  

Inputs\:
    date - The date to parse/convert.
    dateFormat - The format of the input date.
Default value\: default date/time format from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS date/time format)
Examples\: unix, yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSXXX, h\:mm a
    dateLocaleLang - The locale language for input dateFormat string. It will be ignored if dateFormat is empty. 
Default value\: default locale language from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale language)
Examples\: en, ja
    dateLocaleCountry - The locale country for input dateFormat string. It will be ignored if dateFormat is empty or dateLocaleLang is empty.
Default value\: default locale country from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale country)
Example\: US, FR
    outFormat - The format of the output date/time.
Default value\: default date/time format from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS date/time format)
Examples\: unix, yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSXXX, h\:mm a
    outLocaleLang - The locale language for output string. It will be ignored if outFormat is empty. 
Default value\: default locale language from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale language)
Examples\: en, ja
    outLocaleCountry - The locale country for output string. It will be ignored if outFormat is empty or outLocaleLang is empty.
Default value\: default locale country from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale country)
Example\: US, FR

Results\:
    returnResult - The date in the new format.

Responses\:
    success - The date was converted.
    failure - The date could not be converted.

Notes\:
    1. If default locale language from the Java environement is English, the input dateFormat is empty and the input outFormat is empty, the input date should be in the format of "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:08 AM". If the user specifies dateFormat as "dd-MM-yyyy HH\:mm\:ss", the input date should be in the format of "13-07-2006 10\:04\:08". If the input outFormat is empty, the result will be "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:08 AM". If the input outFormat is "yyyy-MM-dd", the result will be "2006-07-13". The dateFormat for "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:078 AM" is "MMM dd, yyyy HH\:mm\:ss a".
    2. Note that the dateFormat and outFormat inputs are case sensitive. 'M' is used for months representation and 'm' for minutes.
    3. Within date and time pattern strings, unquoted letters from 'A' to 'Z' and from 'a' to 'z' are interpreted as pattern letters representing the components of a date or time string. Text can be quoted using single quotes (') to avoid interpretation. "''" represents a single quote. All other characters are not interpreted; they're simply copied into the output string during formatting or matched against the input string during parsing. The following pattern letters are defined (all other characters from 'A' to 'Z' and from 'a' to 'z' are reserved)\:

Letter	Date or Time Component			Presentation		Examples
G	Era designator				Text		AD
y	Year				Year		1996; 96
Y	Week year				Year		2009; 09
M	Month in year				Month		July; Jul; 07
w	Week in year				Number		27
W	Week in month				Number		2
D	Day in year				Number		189
d	Day in month				Number		10
F	Day of week in month			Number		2
E	Day name in week			Text		Tuesday; Tue
u	Day number of week (1 \= Monday, ..., 7 \= Sunday)	Number		1
a	Am/pm marker				Text		PM
H	Hour in day (0-23)			Number		0
k	Hour in day (1-24)			Number		24
K	Hour in am/pm (0-11)			Number		0
h	Hour in am/pm (1-12)			Number		12
m	Minute in hour				Number		30
s	Second in minute			Number		55
S	Millisecond				Number		978
z	Time zone				General time zone	Pacific Standard Time; PST; GMT-08\:00
Z	Time zone				RFC 822 time zone	-800
X	Time zone				ISO 8601 time zone	-08; -0800; -08\:00
Special case\:
unix	Unix timestamp			Number		1384326000

Examples for the date 2001-07-04 12\:08\:56 in U.S. Pacific Time\:

Date			DateFromat			DateLocaleLang	DateLocaleCountry
2001.07.04 AD at 12\:08\:56 PDT	yyyy.MM.dd G 'at' HH\:mm\:ss z		en		US
Wed, Jul 4, '01			EEE, MMM d, ''yy		en		US
2001-07-04T12\:08\:56.235+0700	yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSZ	en		US
2001-07-04T12\:08\:56.235-07\:00	yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSXXX	en		US
1309781336			unix			-		-
b6a8cf67-538b-4919-af6f-923a72666f19.5b358826-87e1-4c56-9c18-2b107022a7be.description=
Performs a mathematical operation on two numbers

Inputs\:
operator - The operation to perform (+, -, *, /, <, >, <\=, >\=, \=\=, \!\=).
value1 - The first value.
value2 - The second value.

Returns\:
The result of the operation, for boolean values this is true or false.

Responses\:
success - The operation completed successfully. If a boolean operation, it evaluated to true.
failure - Something went wrong or the boolean operation returned false.

b6a8cf67-538b-4919-af6f-923a72666f19.761bef29-3b9f-4ebf-ab32-c20006e1de40.description=This operation runs a SQL command. Inputs\: DBServerName - The hostname or ip address of the database server. DbType - The type of database to connect to. Valid values\: Oracle, MSSQL, Sybase, Netcool, DB2 and Custom. Default value\: Oracle Username - The username to use when connecting to the database. Password - The password to use when connecting to the database. instance - The name instance (for MSSQL Server). Leave it blank for default instance. DbPort - The port to connect to. Default values\: Oracle\: 1521, MSSQL\: 1433, Sybase\: 5000, Netcool\: 4100, DB2\: 50000. Database - The name of the database. authenticationType - The type of authentication used to access the database (applicable only to MSSQL type). Valid values\: sql, windows (for MSSQL) Default value\: sql dbClass - The classname of the JDBC driver to use. dbURL - The url required to load up the driver and make your connection. Command - The command to execute. timeout - Seconds to wait before timing out the SQL command execution. When the default value is used, there is no limit on the amount of time allowed for a running command to complete. Default value\: 0 databasePoolingProperties - Properties for database pooling configuration. This parameter replaces the databasePooling.properties file from 9x version (you may copy-paste the file content here). Pooling is disabled by default. For more details check the /Library/Operations/Database/JDBC folder description. Example\: db.pooling.enable\=true resultSetType - the result set type. See JDBC folder description for more details. Valid values\: TYPE_FORWARD_ONLY, TYPE_SCROLL_INSENSITIVE,TYPE_SCROLL_SENSITIVE. Default value\: TYPE_FORWARD_ONLY resultSetConcurrency - the result set concurrency. See JDBC folder description for more details. Valid values\: CONCUR_READ_ONLY, CONCUR_UPDATABLE Default value\: CONCUR_READ_ONLY Results\: returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the "Command completed successfully" message if the operation succeeded, or a failure message otherwise. outputText - The return result of SQL command. updateCount - The update count of the command executed. Responses\: success - The command was executed successfully. failure - Failed to execute the command. Note\: 1. Check the JDBC folder description for details on how to load database connectors. 2. This operation waits for the number of seconds specified in the "seconds" input.

Inputs\:
    seconds - The number of seconds to wait.

Results\:
    resultString – This is the primary output. It contains the "completed sleep" message if the operation completed successfully and an error message otherwise. 

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.
b6a8cf67-538b-4919-af6f-923a72666f19.a4ced0aa-97e8-408a-88d7-a71eedcf1e4e.description=
 
Check to see if the value stored in a specified flow variable, denoted by key, is null.

Inputs\:
    keyName - The key to check, i.e. the name of the flow variable. 
    trimSpaces - If set on "true" then all the whitespaces will be removed from the value stored. 
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false

Returns\: 
    The value in the specified key, i.e. flow variable with all whitespaces removed.

Responses\:
    isNull - If the key is a null pointer, i.e. the flow variable doesn't have an assigned value.
    notNull - If some value is stored in the key, i.e the flow variable has a value assigned. 

Notes\: 
    1. If the "trimSpaces" input is set on "true" and the value from "keyName" contains only whitespaces then the response will be "isNull". 
    2. If the "trimSpaces" input is set on "false" and the value from "keyName" contains only whitespaces then the response will be "notNull". 
    3. If any other value than "true" or "false" is passed on "trimSpaces" input then the default value (false) will be used.
b6a8cf67-538b-4919-af6f-923a72666f19.a8b57264-4192-4f7f-be06-0eac0eff6b84.transition.description=REGISTROS RETORNADOS\: ${queryCount} b6a8cf67-538b-4919-af6f-923a72666f19.bc918f7f-64be-4d20-afe4-31041027ae9c.prompt=AÑO FACTURACION (YYYY)\: b6a8cf67-538b-4919-af6f-923a72666f19.c38a7c07-6370-4e51-99f5-49f459054196.description=
This operation writes the data from "contents" input to the requested file. The operation can be used to overwrite existing content of the file, append extra lines to it or even create a new file.

Inputs\:
    source -  Full path to file. If the file does not exist it is created first.
    contents - The content that should be written to the file. This input field can contain more lines, separated by a delimiter. If it contains the new line character (\n or \r\n), but this is not the delimiter, this character will be escaped and written to file.  
Example\: "This is line no. 01\nThis is line no. 2\n" where \n is the delimiter.
    delimiter - Specifies the newline delimiter that is used to split the "contents" input field into separate lines that will be further written to the given file.
Examples\: \n, \r\n, etc
    characterSet - The character encoding used to write to the file. 
Default\: UTF-8. 
Valid values\: windows-1252, UTF-16, UTF-16BE,  ISO-8859-1, US-ASCII, Shift_JIS etc.
    overwrite - Specifies whether to overwrite the file or append to it. 
Default\: true. 
Valid values\: true, false or the empty string. If this is left empty, the file will be overwritten.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the "success" confirmation message if the operation successfully completes, or an exception message otherwise.
    returnCode - It has the value 0 if the operation successfully completes and 1 otherwise.
    exception - This contains an exception message if the operation fails.

Responses\:
    success - File/directory was written successfully.
    failure - Unable to write to file/directory, empty contents or source.

Examples\:
1. This is a valid input example for using this operation on Windows\:
    source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
    contents\: line1,line2,line3
    delimiter\: ,

2. This is a valid input example for using this operation on Linux\:
    source\: /root/example.txt
    contents\: line1,line2,line3
    delimiter\: ,

staticBinding.value:
WITH TEMPORAL AS ( SELECT TRIM(B.CODIGO_BANCO) AS CV_BANCO, NVL(TRIM(B.CODIGO_BANCO_P),'NA') BANCO_P,
(CASE WHEN TRIM(B.CODIGO_BANCO) = 'VISA' THEN ROUND(NVL((SELECT SUM(C.UIM_SUBTOTAL) FROM TBL_RED_USO_INFRA_MENSUAL C WHERE C.UIM_SERVICIO ='UDI' AND C.UIM_MES_FACT=${UIM_MES_FACT} AND C.UIM_ANIO_FACT=${UIM_ANIO_FACT} AND TRIM(C.UIM_BAN_CODIGO_BANCO) = 'VISA1'),0),2)
WHEN TRIM(B.CODIGO_BANCO) = 'MDS' THEN ROUND(NVL((SELECT SUM(C.UIM_SUBTOTAL) FROM TBL_RED_USO_INFRA_MENSUAL C WHERE C.UIM_SERVICIO ='UDI' AND C.UIM_MES_FACT=${UIM_MES_FACT} AND C.UIM_ANIO_FACT=${UIM_ANIO_FACT} AND TRIM(C.UIM_BAN_CODIGO_BANCO) IN ('MDS4','MDS5','MDS6')),0),2)
WHEN TRIM(B.CODIGO_BANCO) IN ('UPAY','JCB1') THEN ROUND(NVL((SELECT (-1)*SUM(C.UIM_SUBTOTAL) FROM TBL_RED_USO_INFRA_MENSUAL C WHERE C.UIM_SERVICIO ='UDI' AND C.UIM_MES_FACT=${UIM_MES_FACT} AND C.UIM_ANIO_FACT=${UIM_ANIO_FACT} AND TRIM(C.UIM_BAN_CODIGO_BANCO) = TRIM(B.CODIGO_BANCO)),0),2)
ELSE ROUND(NVL((SELECT SUM(C.UIM_SUBTOTAL) FROM TBL_RED_USO_INFRA_MENSUAL C WHERE C.UIM_SERVICIO ='UDI' AND C.UIM_MES_FACT=${UIM_MES_FACT} AND C.UIM_ANIO_FACT=${UIM_ANIO_FACT} AND TRIM(C.UIM_BAN_CODIGO_BANCO) = TRIM(B.CODIGO_BANCO)),0),2) END) AS CREDITO,
(CASE WHEN TRIM(B.CODIGO_BANCO) = 'VISA' THEN ROUND(NVL((SELECT SUM(C.UIM_SUBTOTAL) FROM TBL_RED_USO_INFRA_MENSUAL C WHERE C.UIM_SERVICIO ='UDI' AND C.UIM_MES_FACT=${UIM_MES_FACT} AND C.UIM_ANIO_FACT=${UIM_ANIO_FACT} AND TRIM(C.UIM_BAN_CODIGO_BANCO) = 'VISA2'),0),2)
WHEN TRIM(B.CODIGO_BANCO) = 'MDS' THEN ROUND(NVL((SELECT SUM(C.UIM_SUBTOTAL) FROM TBL_RED_USO_INFRA_MENSUAL C WHERE C.UIM_SERVICIO ='UDI' AND C.UIM_MES_FACT=${UIM_MES_FACT} AND C.UIM_ANIO_FACT=${UIM_ANIO_FACT} AND TRIM(C.UIM_BAN_CODIGO_BANCO) IN ('MDS1','MDS2','MDS3')),0),2)
WHEN TRIM(B.CODIGO_BANCO) IN ('UPAY','JCB1') THEN ROUND(NVL((SELECT (-1)*SUM(C.UIM_SUBTOTAL) FROM TBL_RED_USO_INFRA_MENSUAL C WHERE C.UIM_SERVICIO ='UDI' AND C.UIM_MES_FACT=${UIM_MES_FACT} AND C.UIM_ANIO_FACT=${UIM_ANIO_FACT} AND TRIM(C.UIM_CODIGO_BANCO) = TRIM(B.CODIGO_BANCO)),0),2)
ELSE ROUND(NVL((SELECT SUM(C.UIM_SUBTOTAL) FROM TBL_RED_USO_INFRA_MENSUAL C WHERE C.UIM_SERVICIO ='UDI' AND C.UIM_MES_FACT=${UIM_MES_FACT} AND C.UIM_ANIO_FACT=${UIM_ANIO_FACT} AND TRIM(C.UIM_CODIGO_BANCO) = TRIM(B.CODIGO_BANCO)),0),2) END) AS DEBITO
FROM BANCOS B ) SELECT A.CV_BANCO, A.BANCO_P,
ROUND( (CASE WHEN A.CV_BANCO IN ('UPAY','JCB1') THEN 1 ELSE -1 END)* (A. CREDITO + NVL((SELECT SUM(B.CREDITO) FROM TEMPORAL B WHERE TRIM(B.BANCO_P)=TRIM(A.CV_BANCO)),0)),2) AS CREDITO,
ROUND( (CASE WHEN A.CV_BANCO IN ('VISA','MDS') THEN 1 ELSE -1 END)* (A.DEBITO + NVL((SELECT SUM(B.DEBITO) FROM TEMPORAL B WHERE TRIM(B.BANCO_P)=TRIM(A.CV_BANCO)),0)),2) AS DEBITO
FROM TEMPORAL A WHERE TRIM(A.BANCO_P) IN ('NA') ORDER BY A.CV_BANCO ASC
